about.summary: Regression modeling, testing, estimation, validation, graphics, prediction, and typesetting by storing enhanced model design attributes in the fit.  'rms' is a collection of functions that assist with and streamline modeling.  It also contains functions for binary and ordinal logistic regression models, ordinal models for continuous Y with a variety of distribution families, and the Buckley-James multiple regression model for right-censored responses, and implements penalized maximum likelihood estimation for logistic and ordinary linear models.  'rms' works with almost any regression model, but it was especially written to work with binary or ordinal regression models, Cox regression, accelerated failure time models, ordinary linear models,	the Buckley-James model, generalized least squares for serially or spatially correlated observations, generalized linear models, and quantile regression.

raw_meta_yaml:
{% set version = "6.7-0" %}
{% set posix = 'm2-' if win else '' %}
{% set native = 'm2w64-' if win else '' %}

package:
  name: r-rms
  version: {{ version|replace("-", "_") }}

source:
  url:
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/rms_{{ version }}.tar.gz
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/Archive/rms/rms_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  sha256: 8b3a14c47e2eafb24d9f0807f50af4b8bb8b44b0ec6bd6f38e0676f5a53dbbff

build:
  merge_build_host: true  # [win]
  number: 1
  rpaths:
    - lib/R/lib/
    - lib/

requirements:
  build:
    - {{ compiler('c') }}              # [not win]
    - {{ compiler('m2w64_c') }}        # [win]
    - {{ compiler('fortran') }}        # [not win]
    - {{ compiler('m2w64_fortran') }}  # [win]
    - {{ posix }}filesystem            # [win]
    - {{ posix }}make
    - {{ posix }}sed                   # [win]
    - {{ posix }}coreutils             # [win]
    - {{ posix }}zip                   # [win]
  host:
    - r-base
    - r-cluster
    - r-colorspace
    - r-digest
    - r-ggplot2
    - r-hmisc >=4.8_0
    - r-htmltable >=1.11.0
    - r-htmltools
    - r-kableextra
    - r-knitr
    - r-lattice
    - r-mass
    - r-multcomp
    - r-nlme >=3.1_123
    - r-polspline
    - r-quantreg
    - r-rpart
    - r-sparsem
    - r-survival
  run:
    - r-base
    - {{ native }}gcc-libs         # [win]
    - r-cluster
    - r-colorspace
    - r-digest
    - r-ggplot2
    - r-hmisc >=4.8_0
    - r-htmltable >=1.11.0
    - r-htmltools
    - r-kableextra
    - r-knitr
    - r-lattice
    - r-mass
    - r-multcomp
    - r-nlme >=3.1_123
    - r-polspline
    - r-quantreg
    - r-rpart
    - r-sparsem
    - r-survival

test:
  commands:
    - $R -e "library('rms')"           # [not win]
    - "\"%R%\" -e \"library('rms')\""  # [win]

about:
  home: https://hbiostat.org/R/rms/
  dev_url: https://github.com/harrelfe/rms
  license: GPL-2.0-or-later
  summary: "Regression modeling, testing, estimation, validation, graphics, prediction, and typesetting by storing enhanced model design attributes in the fit.  'rms' is a collection of functions that assist with and streamline modeling.  It also contains functions for binary and ordinal logistic regression models, ordinal
    models for continuous Y with a variety of distribution families, and the Buckley-James multiple regression model for right-censored responses, and implements penalized maximum likelihood estimation for logistic and ordinary linear models.  'rms' works with almost any regression model, but it was especially written to
    work with binary or ordinal regression models, Cox regression, accelerated failure time models, ordinary linear models,\tthe Buckley-James model, generalized least squares for serially or spatially correlated observations, generalized linear models, and quantile regression."
  license_family: GPL2
  license_file:
    - {{ environ["PREFIX"] }}/lib/R/share/licenses/GPL-2
    - {{ environ["PREFIX"] }}/lib/R/share/licenses/GPL-3

extra:
  recipe-maintainers:
    - conda-forge/r
